  <abstract displayLabel="Description">Smith describes McKinley High School's impact on Baton Rouge's racial, political, economic and social history. He recalls the importance of academics, athletics, and school pride during his years as a student there in the 1940s. He lists his role models, inspiring teachers and his accomplishments.</abstract>
  <abstract displayLabel="Link to Abstract">http://www.lib.lsu.edu/sites/all/files/oralhistory/abstracts/mckinley/1_history/Smith_Charles_T936.pdf</abstract>
  <note type="content" displayLabel="Note">This collection includes materials accessioned as Mss. 4700.0646; A digital version of the transcript (pdf) exists for duplication purposes; A digital version of the audio recording (mp3) exists for duplication purposes and public access in the Special Collections Reading Room; Interview conducted by Shawnda Hollins and Carmen Posey.</note>
  <note type="biographical/historical" displayLabel="Biographical Note">Reverend Charles T. Smith graduated from McKinley High School in 1948. He attended Southern University and the New Orleans Baptist Theological Seminary and received his Doctor of Divinity from Union Baptist Theological Seminary. He serves as the pastor of Shiloh Missionary Baptist Church in Baton Rouge.</note>
